{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511096"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:37:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11699"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11699"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.42,0.15,0.13,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4314"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114867"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4314"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1597"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39190"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114867"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man is admitted to hospital with a two-day history of lower abdominal pain, shifting to the right iliac fossa. On abdominal examination, there is tenderness and guarding in the right iliac fossa and a diagnosis of acute appendicitis is made. An emergency laparoscopy is performed and a perforated appendix identified, with gross peritoneal soiling. An appendicectomy and washout is performed. The patient is making a steady post-operative recovery, but on day three has a large vomit. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most the likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paralytic ileus","Acute gastric dilatation","Gastric volvulus","Pseudo-obstruction","Pancreatic pseudocyst"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute gastric dilatation\u003C/strong\u003E. Acute gastric dilatation is characterised with a radiological finding of a massively enlarged stomach. Although it is uncommon, it can be associated with high mortality if treatment is delayed. There are several potential causes of acute gastric dilatation including mechanical and non-mechanical causes: gastric tumours, pancreatic cancer, pyloric stenosis, and surgical adhesions for example or eating disorders and electrolyte imbalances. In the post-operative setting, acute gastric dilatation could be the result of anaesthesia, opioids and immobility. Dehydration and electrolyte imbalances may also contribute.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is most likely in this case that this is a non-mechanical aetiology but regardless, treatment is of prompt nasogastric tube (NGT) insertion for stomach decompression. Otherwise the pressure can lead to venous infarction and gastric perforation. This is a surgical emergency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParalytic ileus \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E are possible but not as likely. It is unusual for patients with paralytic ileus or pseuo-obstruction to present with such a severely enlarged stomach. Common radiological findings include grossly distended bowel loops - small and large bowel respectively. Regardless, the immediate management is also decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E is a relatively rare condition in which patients present with the Borchardt\u0027s triad; pain, vomiting, and inability to pass a nasogastric tube. A plain film will show a single spherical bubble in chest. However, this CT clearly shows an intra-abdominal stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic pseudocyst\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most likely diagnosis as the patient does not have a history of pancreatitis. There are also no signs of pancreatic pseudocyst on the CT-scan that is provided.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with acute gastric dilatation should receive nasogastric tube (NGT) for stomach decompression."],"references":["Shaikh DH, Jyala A, Mehershahi S, et al. Acute Gastric Dilatation: A Cause for Concern. Case Rep Gastroenterol 2021;15:171-77. Available at: https://karger.com/crg/article/15/1/171/93164/Acute-Gastric-Dilatation-A-Cause-for-Concern#","Wee J. Gastric Volvulus in Adults. In: UpToDate [online]. 2022; cited 2022 Jul. Available via: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/gastric-volvulus-in-adults?search=gastric%20volvulus\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~16\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11699"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16298"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16298"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/92fcca86-44d0-475c-9d5e-0efde202fea9.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/92fcca86-44d0-475c-9d5e-0efde202fea9.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":537,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T11:52:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T11:53:16+09:30"},"relation